result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (4th) and Operating w/ PAC (4th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (4th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Charles Wesley Karns was found guilty of OWI (4th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Must contact Probation to report as soon as possible.
Lifetime revocation of driver's license. If eligible, may apply for reinstatement through the Department of Transportation after 10 years. (Call the Department of Transportation with questions).

The Department of Transportation will determine the length of an Ignition Interlock Device (IID) requirement if defendant obtains eligibility for a valid driver's license through the Department. Ignition Interlock Device shall be installed in all vehicles registered under Defendant's name. IID shall be installed prior to Defendant obtaining a valid driver's license or occupational license. However the length of Ignition Interlock Device will begin when a valid driver's license or occupational license has been issued by the Department of Transportation. Call the Department of Transportation with questions.

miscConds.notes: $2,502.00 fine/costs to be paid to the Clerk of Court's Office within 60 days or set up payment plan. Failure to pay may result in a tax intercept, license suspension, warrant and/or civil judgment subject to collection efforts.

$250.00 DNA surcharge to be paid to the Clerk of Court's Office within 60 days or set up payment plan. Failure to pay may result in a tax intercept, license suspension, warrant and/or civil judgment subject to collection efforts.
Must complete an AODA assessment and comply with recommendations.

Absolute sobriety.

No alcohol.

No drugs without a prescription and only in amount prescribed.

Cannot vote until civil rights restored, cannot hold elected office, other civil rights may be lost until restored. If not a US citizen, may face deportation or loss of other citizenship rights.
May not possess or use firearms and, if considered a violent felony, no body armor.

Must provide a DNA sample.  Under Wisconsin Statute 165.76, you are required to provide a biological specimen to the Wisconsin Department of Justice for deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) testing.  If you fail to provide a DNA sample, you may be held in contempt and subject to sanctions or charged with a new crime.

timeConds.notes:
120 days conditional jail must be served up front. Subject to good time. Subject to work release after first 48 hours. Court finds 2 days credit counts as defendant serving first 48 hours without work release. Any electronic monitoring eligibility is subject to jail's policy and rules. Must report to jail immediately after hearing.  

140 days banked for Probation to use if necessary. Not subject to good time.
